CLOUD COMPUTING LAB - PROGRAM 1
PROGRAM 1: Launch an Ubuntu Server by Creating VPC and Route Table in AWS

# Step-by-Step Execution

---

## Step 1: Login to AWS Console

1. Open AWS Management Console.
2. Select region:

```text
Asia Pacific Mumbai / ap-south-1
In the AWS search bar, search:
VPC
Open VPC Dashboard.
Step 2: Create Custom VPC
Go to:
VPC Dashboard → Your VPCs
Click:
Create VPC
Select:
VPC only
Enter the following details:
Name tag: Lab-VPC
IPv4 CIDR block: 10.1.0.0/16
IPv6 CIDR block: No IPv6 CIDR block
Tenancy: Default
Click:
Create VPC
Step 3: Create Public Subnet
Go to:
VPC Dashboard → Subnets
Click:
Create subnet
Select the created VPC:
VPC: Lab-VPC
Enter subnet details:
Subnet name: Public-Subnet
Availability Zone: ap-south-1a
IPv4 subnet CIDR block: 10.1.1.0/24
Click:
Create subnet
Step 4: Enable Auto-Assign Public IPv4

This step is very important because the EC2 instance needs a public IP address for SSH connection.

Go to:
VPC Dashboard → Subnets
Select:
Public-Subnet
Click:
Actions → Edit subnet settings
Enable:
Auto-assign public IPv4 address
Click:
Save
Step 5: Create Internet Gateway
Go to:
VPC Dashboard → Internet Gateways
Click:
Create internet gateway
Enter name:
Lab-IGW
Click:
Create internet gateway
Select the created internet gateway:
Lab-IGW
Click:
Actions → Attach to VPC
Select:
Lab-VPC
Click:
Attach internet gateway
Step 6: Create Route Table
Go to:
VPC Dashboard → Route Tables
Click:
Create route table
Enter the following details:
Name: Public-RT
VPC: Lab-VPC
Click:
Create route table
Step 7: Add Internet Route to Route Table
Select:
Public-RT
Open the Routes tab.
Click:
Edit routes
Click:
Add route
Enter the following route:
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
Target: Internet Gateway
Internet Gateway: Lab-IGW
Click:
Save changes

The final route table should contain:

10.1.0.0/16  → local
0.0.0.0/0    → Lab-IGW
Step 8: Associate Route Table with Public Subnet
Select:
Public-RT
Go to:
Subnet associations
Click:
Edit subnet associations
Select:
Public-Subnet
Click:
Save associations

Now the subnet becomes public because it is connected to the internet through the Internet Gateway.

Step 9: Create Security Group
Open EC2 Dashboard.
Go to:
Security Groups
Click:
Create security group
Enter the following details:
Security group name: Lab-SG
Description: Allow SSH access
VPC: Lab-VPC
Add inbound rule:
Type: SSH
Protocol: TCP
Port: 22
Source: My IP

If SSH does not work in the college lab network, use:

Source: Anywhere IPv4
0.0.0.0/0
Keep outbound rule as default:
All traffic allowed
Click:
Create security group
Step 10: Create Key Pair
Go to:
EC2 Dashboard → Key Pairs
Click:
Create key pair
Enter the following details:
Name: cloud-lab-key
Key pair type: RSA
Private key file format: .pem
Click:
Create key pair
The key file will be downloaded:
cloud-lab-key.pem

Keep this file safely because it is required for SSH login.

Step 11: Launch Ubuntu EC2 Instance
Go to:
EC2 Dashboard → Instances
Click:
Launch instances
Enter instance name:
Ubuntu-Server
Select AMI:
Ubuntu Server
Select instance type:
t2.micro

or

t3.micro
Select key pair:
cloud-lab-key
In Network settings, click:
Edit
Select the following:
VPC: Lab-VPC
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Auto-assign public IP: Enable
Firewall: Select existing security group
Security Group: Lab-SG
Keep storage as default:
8 GB
Click:
Launch instance
Wait until:
Instance state: Running
Status check: 2/2 checks passed
Step 12: Connect to EC2 Instance from Ubuntu Terminal
Open Ubuntu terminal on your local system.
Go to the folder where the key pair is downloaded:
cd ~/Downloads
Change the permission of the key file:
chmod 400 cloud-lab-key.pem
Copy the Public IPv4 address of the EC2 instance from AWS Console.
Connect to the EC2 instance using SSH:
ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@PUBLIC-IP

Example:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@13.201.xx.xx
If it asks for confirmation, type:
yes
After successful connection, the terminal will show:
-a
